description:
Single pale capped Pantherinoid/Gemmatoid Amanita fruiting directly beneath Douglas fir.
Cap: pale, dingy white cap with hints of honey yellow toward disc. Vellum scant, small but adhering strongly to cuticle.
6.8cm wide at maturity.

Harvested entire specimen.

description:
Single fruiting on the side of Henderson Blvd. beneath mature Douglas fir.
Cap cuticle: brown, cap velum cottony and slightly pyramidiform.
Stem: squat, with thick partial veil.
Volva: collar like, slightly flared at margin.
After I shot a short instructional field video and all field photos with my iPhone11 Pro Max, I harvested the specimen.
Once I got back home I also shot an instructional workup video step by step with my iPhone11 Pro Max in my right hand. I removed a single gill and mounted in 3% KOH on a glass slide for microscopy. I then repeated all microscopy steps at 100X and 400X magnification while shooting photos in my right hand with my iPhone11 Pro Max, as well.
MICROSCOPY:
Spores: broadly ellipsoid to nearly subglobose. Many with a small apiculus on one side. Smooth, medium/lg.
Pleurocystidia: broadly truncate to round. Thick walled.
I sliced cap into multiple strips and stem in half to dehydrate for over 24hrs in my Nesco dehydrator. I bagged all specimens in ziplock after dehydration and dated/labeled the bag for my fungal herbarium/genetic record.
